		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Radio</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">This article is about radio as a technology.  For other uses, including radio broadcasting as an art form, see <a href="/wiki/Radio_(disambiguation)" title="Radio (disambiguation)">Radio (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:The_PVR.jpg" class="image" title="Classic radio receiver dial"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/The_PVR.jpg/250px-The_PVR.jpg" width="250" height="187" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:The_PVR.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Classic radio <a href="/wiki/Receiver_(radio)" title="Receiver (radio)">receiver</a> dial</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="noprint tright portal" style="border:solid #aaa 1px;margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 0.5em;">
<table style="background:#f9f9f9; font-size:85%; line-height:110%;">
<tr>
<td><a href="/wiki/File:Radio_icon.png" class="image" title="Radio icon.png"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1d/Radio_icon.png" width="32" height="23" border="0" /></a></td>
<td style="padding:0 0.2em;"><i><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Radio" title="Portal:Radio">Radio portal</a></b></i></td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<p><b>Radio</b> is the transmission of signals by <a href="/wiki/Modulation" title="Modulation">modulation</a> of <a href="/wiki/Electromagnetic_radiation" title="Electromagnetic radiation">electromagnetic waves</a> with <a href="/wiki/Frequency" title="Frequency">frequencies</a> below those of <a href="/wiki/Visible_light" title="Visible light" class="mw-redirect">visible light</a>. Electromagnetic radiation <a href="/wiki/Radio_propagation" title="Radio propagation">travels</a> by means of oscillating <a href="/wiki/Electromagnetic_field" title="Electromagnetic field">electromagnetic fields</a> that pass through the air and the <a href="/wiki/Vacuum" title="Vacuum">vacuum</a> of space. Information is carried by systematically changing (<a href="/wiki/Modulation" title="Modulation">modulating</a>) some property of the radiated waves, such as <a href="/wiki/Amplitude" title="Amplitude">amplitude</a>, <a href="/wiki/Frequency" title="Frequency">frequency</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Phase_(waves)" title="Phase (waves)">phase</a>. When radio waves pass an electrical conductor, the oscillating fields induce an alternating current in the conductor. This can be <a href="/wiki/Demodulation" title="Demodulation">detected</a> and transformed into sound or other signals that carry information.</p>
